<p><b>Set theory</b> is the branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematical_logic" title=3D"Mathematical logic">mathematical logic</a>=
 that studies <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)" t=
itle=3D"Set (mathematics)">sets</a>, which can be informally described as c=
ollections of objects. Although objects of any kind can be collected into a=
 set, set theory =E2=80=93 as a branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathematics">mathematics</a> =E2=80=93 is mos=
tly concerned with those that are relevant to mathematics as a whole.
</p><p>The modern study of set theory was initiated by the German mathemati=
cians <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Dedekind" title=3D"R=
ichard Dedekind">Richard Dedekind</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Georg_Cantor" title=3D"Georg Cantor">Georg Cantor</a> in the 1870s.=
 In particular, Georg Cantor is commonly considered the founder of set theo=
ry. The non-formalized systems investigated during this early stage go unde=
r the name of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_set_theory"=
 title=3D"Naive set theory">naive set theory</a></i>. After the discovery o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paradoxes_of_set_theory" title=
=3D"Paradoxes of set theory">paradoxes within naive set theory</a> (such as=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell%27s_paradox" title=3D"Rus=
sell's paradox">Russell's paradox</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Cantor%27s_paradox" title=3D"Cantor's paradox">Cantor's paradox</a> an=
d the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burali-Forti_paradox" title=
=3D"Burali-Forti paradox">Burali-Forti paradox</a>), various <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatic_system" title=3D"Axiomatic system">axi=
omatic systems</a> were proposed in the early twentieth century, of which <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fraenkel_set_theory=
" title=3D"Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory">Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel se=
t theory</a> (with or without the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Axiom_of_choice" title=3D"Axiom of choice">axiom of choice</a>) is still th=
e best-known and most studied.
</p><p>Set theory is commonly employed as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Foundation_of_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Foundat=
ion of mathematics">foundational system for the whole of mathematics</a>, p=
articularly in the form of Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory with the axi=
om of choice. Besides its foundational role, set theory also provides the f=
ramework to develop a mathematical theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Infinity" title=3D"Infinity">infinity</a>, and has various appli=
cations in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=
=3D"Computer science">computer science</a> (such as in the theory of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relational_algebra" title=3D"Relational =
algebra">relational algebra</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Philosophy" title=3D"Philosophy">philosophy</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Semantics_(computer_science)" title=3D"Semantics (computer s=
cience)">formal semantics</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Evolutionary_dynamics" title=3D"Evolutionary dynamics">evolutionary dynami=
cs</a>. Its foundational appeal, together with its <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Paradoxes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Paradoxes">parad=
oxes</a>, and its implications for the concept of infinity and its multiple=
 applications have made set theory an area of major interest for <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic" title=3D"Logic">logicians</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_mathematics" title=3D"P=
hilosophy of mathematics">philosophers of mathematics</a>. Contemporary res=
earch into set theory covers a vast array of topics, ranging from the struc=
ture of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"=
Real number">real number</a> line to the study of the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consistency" title=3D"Consistency">consistency</a> of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_cardinal" title=3D"Large card=
inal">large cardinals</a>.
</p>
