></figcaption></figure>
<p>The basic notion of grouping objects has existed since at least the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number#History" title=3D"Natur=
al number">emergence of numbers</a>, and the notion of treating sets as the=
ir own objects has existed since at least the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Tree_of_Porphyry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tree of Porphy=
ry">Tree of Porphyry</a> in 3rd-century AD. The simplicity and ubiquity of =
sets makes it hard to determine the origin of sets as now used in mathemati=
cs; however, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Bolzano" titl=
e=3D"Bernard Bolzano">Bernard Bolzano</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Paradoxes_of_the_Infinite" title=3D"Paradoxes of the Infinite"=
>Paradoxes of the Infinite</a></i> (<i>Paradoxien des Unendlichen</i>, 1851=
) is generally considered the first rigorous introduction of sets to mathem=
atics. In his work, he (among other things) expanded on <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Galileo%27s_paradox" title=3D"Galileo's paradox">Gali=
leo's paradox</a>, and introduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
One-to-one_correspondence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"One-to-one corres=
pondence">one-to-one correspondence</a> of infinite sets, for example betwe=
en the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interval_(mathematics)" tit=
le=3D"Interval (mathematics)">intervals</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element=
 mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-ma=
thml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/M=
ath/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle [0,5]}">
