//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>
Before mathematical set theory, basic concepts of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Infinity" title=3D"Infinity">infinity</a> were considered t=
o be in the domain of philosophy (see: <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Infinity_(philosophy)" title=3D"Infinity (philosophy)">Infinity (ph=
ilosophy)</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinity#=
History" title=3D"Infinity">Infinity =C2=A7&nbsp;History</a></i>). Since th=
e 5th century BC, beginning with Greek philosopher <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Zeno_of_Elea" title=3D"Zeno of Elea">Zeno of Elea</a> in t=
he West (and early <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathemat=
ics" title=3D"Indian mathematics">Indian mathematicians</a> in the East), m=
athematicians had struggled with the concept of infinity. With the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_calculus" title=3D"History of =
calculus">development of calculus</a> in the late 17th century, philosopher=
s began to generally distinguish between potential and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Actual_infinity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Actual=
 infinity">actual infinity</a>, wherein mathematics was only considered in =
the latter.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">C=
arl Friedrich Gauss</a> famously stated: </p><blockquote><p>Infinity is not=
hing more than a figure of speech which helps us talk about limits. The not=
ion of a completed infinity doesn't belong in mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theo=
ry#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote><p>Development of mathematical s=
et theory was motivated by several mathematicians. <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Bernhard_Riemann" title=3D"Bernhard Riemann">Bernhard Riem=
ann</a>'s lecture <i>On the Hypotheses which lie at the Foundations of Geom=
etry</i> (1854) proposed new ideas about <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Topology" title=3D"Topology">topology</a>. His lectures also introdu=
ced the concept of basing mathematics in terms of sets or <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manifold" title=3D"Manifold">manifolds</a> in the s=
ense of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Class_(set_theory)" titl=
e=3D"Class (set theory)">class</a> (which he called <i>Mannigfaltigkeit</i>=
) now called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point-set_topology" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Point-set topology">point-set topology</a>. T=
he lecture was published by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richar=
d_Dedekind" title=3D"Richard Dedekind">Richard Dedekind</a> in 1868, along =
with Riemann's paper on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonomet=
ric_series" title=3D"Trigonometric series">trigonometric series</a> (which =
presented the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemann_integral" ti=
tle=3D"Riemann integral">Riemann integral</a>), The latter was the starting=
 point for a movement in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_anal=
ysis" title=3D"Real analysis">real analysis</a> of the study of =E2=80=9Cse=
riously=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discontinuous_fun=
ction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discontinuous function">discontinuous=
 functions</a>. A young <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg_Cant=
or" title=3D"Georg Cantor">Georg Cantor</a> entered into this area, which l=
ed him to the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_set" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Point set">point-sets</a>. Around 1871, infl=
uenced by Riemann, Dedekind began working with sets in his publications, wh=
ich dealt very clearly and precisely with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Equivalence_relations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Equivalence r=
elations">equivalence relations</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Partition_of_a_set" title=3D"Partition of a set">partitions of sets</a>,=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homomorphisms" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Homomorphisms">homomorphisms</a>. Thus, many of the usual =
set-theoretic procedures of twentieth-century mathematics go back to his wo=
rk. However, he did not publish a formal explanation of his set theory unti=
l 1888.
</p><div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Naive_set_theory">Naive=
 set theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Set_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Naive =
set theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_set_theory" ti=
tle=3D"Naive set theory">Naive set theory</a></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Georg_Cantor_1894.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https:=
//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Georg_Cantor_1894.jpg/2=
50px-Georg_Cantor_1894.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"160" height=3D"230"=
 class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"271" data-file-height=3D"389"=
></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg_Cantor" tit=
le=3D"Georg Cantor">Georg Cantor</a>, 1894</figcaption></figure>
<p>Set theory, as understood by modern mathematicians, is generally conside=
red to be founded by a single paper in 1874 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Georg_Cantor" title=3D"Georg Cantor">Georg Cantor</a> titled <=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_a_Property_of_the_Collection_=
of_All_Real_Algebraic_Numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"On a Property=
 of the Collection of All Real Algebraic Numbers">On a Property of the Coll=
ection of All Real Algebraic Numbers</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cantor1874=
_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theo=
ry#cite_note-cantor1874-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-6"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In his paper, he developed=
 the notion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinality" title=
=3D"Cardinality">cardinality</a>, comparing the sizes of two sets by settin=
g them in one-to-one correspondence. His "revolutionary discovery" was that=
 the set of all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=
=3D"Real number">real numbers</a> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Uncountable_set" title=3D"Uncountable set">uncountable</a>, that is, one=
 cannot put all real numbers in a list. This theorem is proved using <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantor%27s_first_set_theory_article#The_=
proofs" title=3D"Cantor's first set theory article">Cantor's first uncounta=
bility proof</a>, which differs from the more familiar proof using his <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantor%27s_diagonal_argument" title=3D=
"Cantor's diagonal argument">diagonal argument</a>.
</p><p>Cantor introduced fundamental constructions in set theory, such as t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_set" title=3D"Power set">=
power set</a> of a set <i>A</i>, which is the set of all possible <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subset" title=3D"Subset">subsets</a> of <=
i>A</i>. He later proved that the size of the power set of <i>A</i> is stri=
ctly larger than the size of <i>A</i>, even when <i>A</i> is an infinite se=
t; this result soon became known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Cantor%27s_theorem" title=3D"Cantor's theorem">Cantor's theorem</a>. Cant=
or developed a theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transfini=
te_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Transfinite numbers">transfinite=
 numbers</a>, called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinal_numb=
er" title=3D"Cardinal number">cardinals</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ordinal_number" title=3D"Ordinal number">ordinals</a>, which =
extended the arithmetic of the natural numbers. His notation for the cardin=
al numbers was the Hebrew letter <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-e=
lement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" =
style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"=
 alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \aleph }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=84=B5<!-- =E2=84=B5 --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \aleph }</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/306c55e6bc96d94db729ff5821c8f45a34c72bce" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.42ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ale=
ph }"></span> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E2%84%B5" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"=E2=84=B5">=E2=84=B5</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Aleph" title=3D"Aleph">aleph</a>) with a natural number subs=
cript; for the ordinals he employed the Greek letter <span class=3D"mwe-mat=
h-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mw=
e-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.o=
rg/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \omega }">
  <semantics>
