However, Frege's work was short-lived, as it was found by <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bertrand_Russell" title=3D"Bertrand Russell">Bertra=
nd Russell</a> that his axioms lead to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Contradiction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Contradiction">contrad=
iction</a>. Specifically, Frege's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Basic_Law_V" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Basic Law V">Basic Law V</a> (n=
ow known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_schema_of_un=
restricted_comprehension" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiom schema of un=
restricted comprehension">axiom schema of unrestricted comprehension</a>). =
According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_Law_V" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Basic Law V">Basic Law V</a>, for any sufficiently w=
ell-defined <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Property_(philosophy)"=
 title=3D"Property (philosophy)">property</a>, there is the set of all and =
only the objects that have that property. The contradiction, called <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell%27s_paradox" title=3D"Russell's p=
aradox">Russell's paradox</a>, is shown as follows:</p><blockquote><p>Let <=
i>R</i> be the set of all sets that are not members of themselves. (This se=
t is sometimes called "the Russell set".) If <i>R</i> is not a member of it=
self, then its definition entails that it is a member of itself; yet, if it=
 is a member of itself, then it is not a member of itself, since it is the =
set of all sets that are not members of themselves. The resulting contradic=
tion is Russell's paradox. In symbols:
