<p>Set theory begins with a fundamental <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Binary_relation" title=3D"Binary relation">binary relation</a> betwee=
n an object <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">o</sp=
an> and a set <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</=
span>. If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">o</span=
> is a <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_membership" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Set membership">member</a></i> (or <i>element</i>) o=
f <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, the n=
otation <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>o</i> =E2=88=88 <i>A</i></span> is used.=
 A set is described by listing elements separated by commas, or by a charac=
terizing property of its elements, within braces { }.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#c=
ite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> Since sets are objects, the membership relation can=
 relate sets as well, i.e., sets themselves can be members of other sets.
</p><p>A derived binary relation between two sets is the subset relation, a=
lso called <i>set inclusion</i>. If all the members of set <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> are also members of set =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span>, then <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> is a <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subset" title=3D"Subset">subset</a><=
/i> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span>, =
denoted <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i> =E2=8A=86 <i>B</i></span>. For exa=
mple, <span class=3D"texhtml">{1, 2}</span> is a subset of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml">{1, 2, 3}</span>, and so is <span class=3D"texhtml">{2}</span> but =
<span class=3D"texhtml">{1, 4}</span> is not. As implied by this definition=
, a set is a subset of itself. For cases where this possibility is unsuitab=
le or would make sense to be rejected, the term <i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Proper_subset" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Proper subse=
t">proper subset</a></i> is defined, variously denoted <span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline =
mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle A\subset B}">
  <semantics>
