> is both a member and a proper subset of the set <span class=3D"texhtml">{=
1, {1}}</span>.
</p><p>Just as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=
=3D"Arithmetic">arithmetic</a> features <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Binary_operation" title=3D"Binary operation">binary operations</a> on=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number" title=3D"Number">numbers<=
/a>, set theory features binary operations on sets.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cit=
e_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> The following is a partial list of them:
</p>
<ul><li><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_(set_theory)" tit=
le=3D"Union (set theory)">Union</a></i> of the sets <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span>, denoted <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>A</i> =E2=88=AA <i>B</i></span>, is the set of all objects that are a memb=
er of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, o=
r <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">B</span>, or bo=
th.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, the union of=
