-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.787ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle V}"=
></span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Formalized_set_theory">Form=
alized set theory</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DSet_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: =
Formalized set theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Axiomatic_set_theory"></span>
Elementary set theory can be studied informally and intuitively, and so can=
 be taught in primary schools using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Venn_diagram" title=3D"Venn diagram">Venn diagrams</a>. The intuitive app=
roach tacitly assumes that a set may be formed from the class of all object=
s satisfying any particular defining condition. This assumption gives rise =
to paradoxes, the simplest and best known of which are <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell%27s_paradox" title=3D"Russell's paradox">Russe=
ll's paradox</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burali-Fo=
rti_paradox" title=3D"Burali-Forti paradox">Burali-Forti paradox</a>. <b>Ax=
iomatic set theory</b> was originally devised to rid set theory of such par=
adoxes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>note 1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The most widely studied systems of axiomatic set theory imply that a=
ll sets form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumulative_hierarch=
y" title=3D"Cumulative hierarchy">cumulative hierarchy</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_th=
eory#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Such systems come in two flavors, those whose=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontology" title=3D"Ontology">onto=
logy</a> consists of:
</p>
<ul><li><i>Sets alone</i>. This includes the most common axiomatic set theo=
ry, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fraenkel_set_t=
heory" title=3D"Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory"><b>Z</b>ermelo=E2=80=
=93<b>F</b>raenkel set theory</a> with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Axiom_of_choice" title=3D"Axiom of choice">axiom of <b>c</b>hoice<=
/a> (ZFC). Fragments of <b>ZFC</b> include:
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo_set_theory" title=
=3D"Zermelo set theory">Zermelo set theory</a>, which replaces the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_schema_of_replacement" title=3D"Axi=
om schema of replacement">axiom schema of replacement</a> with that of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_schema_of_separation" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Axiom schema of separation">separation</a>;</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_set_theory" title=3D"G=
eneral set theory">General set theory</a>, a small fragment of Zermelo set =
theory sufficient for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peano_ax=
ioms" title=3D"Peano axioms">Peano axioms</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Finite_set" title=3D"Finite set">finite sets</a>;</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kripke%E2%80%93Platek_set_theo=
ry" title=3D"Kripke=E2=80=93Platek set theory">Kripke=E2=80=93Platek set th=
eory</a>, which omits the axioms of infinity, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Axiom_of_power_set" title=3D"Axiom of power set">powerset</a>, =
and choice, and weakens the axiom schemata of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Axiom_schema_of_separation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axio=
m schema of separation">separation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Axiom_schema_of_replacement" title=3D"Axiom schema of replacement"=
>replacement</a>.</li></ul></li>
<li><i>Sets and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proper_class" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Proper class">proper classes</a></i>. These incl=
ude <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Neumann%E2%80%93Bernays%E2=
%80%93G%C3%B6del_set_theory" title=3D"Von Neumann=E2=80=93Bernays=E2=80=93G=
=C3=B6del set theory">Von Neumann=E2=80=93Bernays=E2=80=93G=C3=B6del set th=
eory</a>, which has the same <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stren=
gth_(mathematical_logic)" title=3D"Strength (mathematical logic)">strength<=
/a> as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZFC" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"ZFC">ZFC</a> for theorems about sets alone, and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morse%E2%80%93Kelley_set_theory" title=3D"Morse=E2=
=80=93Kelley set theory">Morse=E2=80=93Kelley set theory</a> and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarski%E2%80%93Grothendieck_set_theory" titl=
e=3D"Tarski=E2=80=93Grothendieck set theory">Tarski=E2=80=93Grothendieck se=
t theory</a>, both of which are stronger than ZFC.</li></ul>
<p>The above systems can be modified to allow <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Urelement" title=3D"Urelement">urelements</a></i>, objects t=
hat can be members of sets but that are not themselves sets and do not have=
 any members. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo_set_theory" =
title=3D"Zermelo set theory">Zermelo set theory</a> was originally defined =
over a domain consisting of both sets and urelements.
</p><p>The <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Foundations" tit=
le=3D"New Foundations">New Foundations</a></i> systems of <b>NFU</b> (allow=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urelement" title=3D"Urelement"=
>urelements</a>) and <b>NF</b> (lacking them), associate with <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willard_Van_Orman_Quine" title=3D"Willard Van O=
rman Quine">Willard Van Orman Quine</a>, are not based on a cumulative hier=
archy. NF and NFU include a "set of everything", relative to which every se=
t has a complement. In these systems urelements matter, because NF, but not=
 NFU, produces sets for which the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Axiom_of_choice" title=3D"Axiom of choice">axiom of choice</a> does not hol=
d. Despite NF's ontology not reflecting the traditional cumulative hierarch=
y and violating well-foundedness, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Thomas_Forster_(mathematician)" title=3D"Thomas Forster (mathematician)">Th=
omas Forster</a> has argued that it does reflect an <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DIterative_conception_of_set&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Iterative conception of set (pa=
ge does not exist)">iterative conception of set</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#ci=
te_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Systems of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructive_set=
_theory" title=3D"Constructive set theory">constructive set theory</a>, suc=
h as CST, CZF, and IZF, embed their set axioms in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Intuitionistic_logic" title=3D"Intuitionistic logic">intuit=
ionistic</a> instead of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_=
logic" title=3D"Classical logic">classical logic</a>. Yet other systems acc=
ept classical logic but feature a nonstandard membership relation. These in=
clude <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rough_set" title=3D"Rough se=
t">rough set theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_=
set_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fuzzy set theory">fuzzy set theo=
ry</a>, in which the value of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
tomic_formula" title=3D"Atomic formula">atomic formula</a> embodying the me=
mbership relation is not simply <b>True</b> or <b>False</b>. The <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean-valued_model" title=3D"Boolean-value=
d model">Boolean-valued models</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/ZFC" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ZFC">ZFC</a> are a related subject.
</p><p>An enrichment of ZFC called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Internal_set_theory" title=3D"Internal set theory">internal set theory</a>=
 was proposed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Nelson" ti=
tle=3D"Edward Nelson">Edward Nelson</a> in 1977.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_n=
ote-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_theory&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Applications"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>Many mathematical concepts can be defined precisely using only set theor=
etic concepts. For example, mathematical structures as diverse as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=3D"Gr=
aph (discrete mathematics)">graphs</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Manifolds" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Manifolds">manifolds</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (=
mathematics)">rings</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_sp=
ace" title=3D"Vector space">vector spaces</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Relational_algebra" title=3D"Relational algebra">relationa=
l algebras</a> can all be defined as sets satisfying various (axiomatic) pr=
operties. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalence_relation" ti=
tle=3D"Equivalence relation">Equivalence</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Order_relation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Order relatio=
n">order relations</a> are ubiquitous in mathematics, and the theory of mat=
hematical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relation_(mathematics)" =
title=3D"Relation (mathematics)">relations</a> can be described in set theo=
ry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_=
note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Set theory is also a promising foundational system for much of mathe=
matics. Since the publication of the first volume of <i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principia_Mathematica" title=3D"Principia Mathematica=
">Principia Mathematica</a></i>, it has been claimed that most (or even all=
) mathematical theorems can be derived using an aptly designed set of axiom=
s for set theory, augmented with many definitions, using <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First-order_logic" title=3D"First-order logic">first=
</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second-order_logic" title=
=3D"Second-order logic">second-order logic</a>. For example, properties of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natur=
al number">natural</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_nu=
mber" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a> can be derived within set theo=
ry, as each of these number systems can be defined by representing their el=
ements as sets of specific forms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-24"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Set theory as a foundation for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">mathematical ana=
lysis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topology" title=3D"Topo=
logy">topology</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algeb=
ra" title=3D"Abstract algebra">abstract algebra</a>, and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_mathematics" title=3D"Discrete mathematics"=
>discrete mathematics</a> is likewise uncontroversial; mathematicians accep=
t (in principle) that theorems in these areas can be derived from the relev=
ant definitions and the axioms of set theory. However, it remains that few =
full derivations of complex mathematical theorems from set theory have been=
 formally verified, since such formal derivations are often much longer tha=
n the natural language proofs mathematicians commonly present. One verifica=
tion project, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metamath" title=3D"M=
etamath">Metamath</a>, includes human-written, computer-verified derivation=
s of more than 12,000 theorems starting from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/ZFC" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ZFC">ZFC</a> set theory, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First-order_logic" title=3D"First-ord=
er logic">first-order logic</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Propositional_logic" title=3D"Propositional logic">propositional logic</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Areas_of_study">Areas of st=
udy</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_theo=
ry&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Areas of study=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Set theory is a major area of research in mathematics with many interrel=
ated subfields:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Combinatorial_set_theory">C=
ombinatorial set theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DSet_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Combinatorial set theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitary_combinato=
rics" title=3D"Infinitary combinatorics">Infinitary combinatorics</a></div>
<p><i>Combinatorial set theory</i> concerns extensions of finite <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorics" title=3D"Combinatorics">combi=
natorics</a> to infinite sets. This includes the study of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinal_arithmetic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Cardinal arithmetic">cardinal arithmetic</a> and the study of extensions o=
f <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramsey%27s_theorem" title=3D"Ram=
sey's theorem">Ramsey's theorem</a> such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Erd%C5%91s%E2%80%93Rado_theorem" title=3D"Erd=C5=91s=E2=80=93=
Rado theorem">Erd=C5=91s=E2=80=93Rado theorem</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Descriptive_set_theory">Des=
criptive set theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DSet_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Descriptive set theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descriptive_set_theo=
ry" title=3D"Descriptive set theory">Descriptive set theory</a></div>
<p><i>Descriptive set theory</i> is the study of subsets of the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rea=
l line">real line</a> and, more generally, subsets of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polish_space" title=3D"Polish space">Polish spaces</a>.=
 It begins with the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point=
class" title=3D"Pointclass">pointclasses</a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Borel_hierarchy" title=3D"Borel hierarchy">Borel hierarch=
y</a> and extends to the study of more complex hierarchies such as the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_hierarchy" title=3D"Project=
ive hierarchy">projective hierarchy</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Wadge_hierarchy" title=3D"Wadge hierarchy">Wadge hierarchy</a=
>. Many properties of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borel_set" t=
itle=3D"Borel set">Borel sets</a> can be established in ZFC, but proving th=
ese properties hold for more complicated sets requires additional axioms re=
lated to determinacy and large cardinals.
</p><p>The field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effective_desc=
riptive_set_theory" title=3D"Effective descriptive set theory">effective de=
scriptive set theory</a> is between set theory and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Recursion_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Recursion=
 theory">recursion theory</a>. It includes the study of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lightface_pointclass" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Lightface pointclass">lightface pointclasses</a>, and is closely related to=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperarithmetical_theory" title=
=3D"Hyperarithmetical theory">hyperarithmetical theory</a>. In many cases, =
results of classical descriptive set theory have effective versions; in som=
e cases, new results are obtained by proving the effective version first an=
d then extending ("relativizing") it to make it more broadly applicable.
</p><p>A recent area of research concerns <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Borel_equivalence_relation" title=3D"Borel equivalence relation">Bo=
rel equivalence relations</a> and more complicated definable <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalence_relation" title=3D"Equivalence relat=
ion">equivalence relations</a>. This has important applications to the stud=
y of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invariant_(mathematics)" titl=
e=3D"Invariant (mathematics)">invariants</a> in many fields of mathematics.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fuzzy_set_theory">Fuzzy set=
 theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_=
theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Fuzzy set=
 theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_set_theory" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fuzzy set theory">Fuzzy set theory</a></div>
<p>In set theory as Cantor defined and Zermelo and Fraenkel axiomatized, an=
 object is either a member of a set or not. In <i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Fuzzy_set_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fuzzy set =
theory">fuzzy set theory</a></i> this condition was relaxed by <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lotfi_A._Zadeh" title=3D"Lotfi A. Zadeh">Lotfi=
 A. Zadeh</a> so an object has a <i>degree of membership</i> in a set, a nu=
mber between 0 and 1. For example, the degree of membership of a person in =
the set of "tall people" is more flexible than a simple yes or no answer an=
d can be a real number such as 0.75.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Inner_model_theory">Inner m=
odel theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Set_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Inner=
 model theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_model_theory" =
title=3D"Inner model theory">Inner model theory</a></div>
<p>An <i>inner model</i> of Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory (ZF) is a t=
ransitive <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proper_class" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Proper class">class</a> that includes all the ordinals=
 and satisfies all the axioms of ZF. The canonical example is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructible_universe" title=3D"Construc=
tible universe">constructible universe</a> <i>L</i> developed by G=C3=B6del=
.
One reason that the study of inner models is of interest is that it can be =
used to prove consistency results. For example, it can be shown that regard=
less of whether a model <i>V</i> of ZF satisfies the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuum_hypothesis" title=3D"Continuum hypothesis">con=
tinuum hypothesis</a> or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom=
_of_choice" title=3D"Axiom of choice">axiom of choice</a>, the inner model =
<i>L</i> constructed inside the original model will satisfy both the genera=
lized continuum hypothesis and the axiom of choice. Thus the assumption tha=
t ZF is consistent (has at least one model) implies that ZF together with t=
hese two principles is consistent.
</p><p>The study of inner models is common in the study of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_of_determinacy" title=3D"Axiom of determinac=
y">determinacy</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_cardi=
nal" title=3D"Large cardinal">large cardinals</a>, especially when consider=
ing axioms such as the axiom of determinacy that contradict the axiom of ch=
oice. Even if a fixed model of set theory satisfies the axiom of choice, it=
 is possible for an inner model to fail to satisfy the axiom of choice. For=
 example, the existence of sufficiently large cardinals implies that there =
is an inner model satisfying the axiom of determinacy (and thus not satisfy=
ing the axiom of choice).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Large_cardinals">Large card=
inals</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_th=
eory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Large cardi=
nals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_cardinal_prope=
rty" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Large cardinal property">Large cardinal=
 property</a></div>
<p>A <i>large cardinal</i> is a cardinal number with an extra property. Man=
y such properties are studied, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Inaccessible_cardinal" title=3D"Inaccessible cardinal">inaccessible =
cardinals</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measurable_cardinal=
" title=3D"Measurable cardinal">measurable cardinals</a>, and many more. Th=
ese properties typically imply the cardinal number must be very large, with=
 the existence of a cardinal with the specified property unprovable in <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fraenkel_set_theory" t=
itle=3D"Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory">Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set t=
heory</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Determinacy">Determinacy</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_theory&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Determinacy"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinacy" title=
=3D"Determinacy">Determinacy</a></div>
<p><i>Determinacy</i> refers to the fact that, under appropriate assumption=
s, certain two-player games of perfect information are determined from the =
start in the sense that one player must have a winning strategy. The existe=
nce of these strategies has important consequences in descriptive set theor=
y, as the assumption that a broader class of games is determined often impl=
ies that a broader class of sets will have a topological property. The <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_of_determinacy" title=3D"Axiom o=
f determinacy">axiom of determinacy</a> (AD) is an important object of stud=
y; although incompatible with the axiom of choice, AD implies that all subs=
ets of the real line are well behaved (in particular, measurable and with t=
he perfect set property). AD can be used to prove that the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wadge_degree" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wadge=
 degree">Wadge degrees</a> have an elegant structure.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Forcing">Forcing</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_theory&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Forcing"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forcing_(mathematics=
)" title=3D"Forcing (mathematics)">Forcing (mathematics)</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Cohen_(mathematician)" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Paul Cohen (mathematician)">Paul Cohen</a> inve=
nted the method of <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forcing_(mat=
hematics)" title=3D"Forcing (mathematics)">forcing</a></i> while searching =
for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_theory" title=3D"Model=
 theory">model</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZFC" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"ZFC">ZFC</a> in which the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Continuum_hypothesis" title=3D"Continuum hypothesis">cont=
inuum hypothesis</a> fails, or a model of ZF in which the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_of_choice" title=3D"Axiom of choice">axiom of=
 choice</a> fails. Forcing adjoins to some given model of set theory additi=
onal sets in order to create a larger model with properties determined (i.e=
. "forced") by the construction and the original model. For example, Cohen'=
s construction adjoins additional subsets of the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural numbers</a>=
 without changing any of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardi=
nal_number" title=3D"Cardinal number">cardinal numbers</a> of the original =
model. Forcing is also one of two methods for proving <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consistency_(mathematical_logic)" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Consistency (mathematical logic)">relative consistency</a> by fin=
itistic methods, the other method being <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Boolean-valued_model" title=3D"Boolean-valued model">Boolean-valued m=
odels</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cardinal_invariants">Cardin=
al invariants</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DSet_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Ca=
rdinal invariants"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinal_characteris=
tics_of_the_continuum" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cardinal characterist=
ics of the continuum">Cardinal characteristics of the continuum</a></div>
<p>A <i>cardinal invariant</i> is a property of the real line measured by a=
 cardinal number. For example, a well-studied invariant is the smallest car=
dinality of a collection of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meagre=
_set" title=3D"Meagre set">meagre sets</a> of reals whose union is the enti=
re real line. These are invariants in the sense that any two isomorphic mod=
els of set theory must give the same cardinal for each invariant. Many card=
inal invariants have been studied, and the relationships between them are o=
ften complex and related to axioms of set theory.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Set-theoretic_topology">Set=
-theoretic topology</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DSet_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Set-theoretic topology"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set-theoretic_topolo=
gy" title=3D"Set-theoretic topology">Set-theoretic topology</a></div>
<p><i>Set-theoretic topology</i> studies questions of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_topology" title=3D"General topology">general to=
pology</a> that are set-theoretic in nature or that require advanced method=
s of set theory for their solution. Many of these theorems are independent =
of ZFC, requiring stronger axioms for their proof. A famous problem is the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moore_space_(topology)" title=3D"M=
oore space (topology)">normal Moore space question</a>, a question in gener=
al topology that was the subject of intense research. The answer to the nor=
mal Moore space question was eventually proved to be independent of ZFC.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Controversy">Controversy</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_theory&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Controversy"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Controversy_over_Can=
tor%27s_theory" title=3D"Controversy over Cantor's theory">Controversy over=
 Cantor's theory</a></div>
<p>From set theory's inception, some mathematicians have objected to it as =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foundations_of_mathematics" titl=
e=3D"Foundations of mathematics">foundation for mathematics</a>. The most c=
ommon objection to set theory, one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Leopold_Kronecker" title=3D"Leopold Kronecker">Kronecker</a> voiced in set=
 theory's earliest years, starts from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mathematical_constructivism" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathema=
tical constructivism">constructivist</a> view that mathematics is loosely r=
elated to computation. If this view is granted, then the treatment of infin=
ite sets, both in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_set_theory=
" title=3D"Naive set theory">naive</a> and in axiomatic set theory, introdu=
ces into mathematics methods and objects that are not computable even in pr=
inciple. The feasibility of constructivism as a substitute foundation for m=
athematics was greatly increased by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Errett_Bishop" title=3D"Errett Bishop">Errett Bishop</a>'s influential bo=
ok <i>Foundations of Constructive Analysis</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_no=
te-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A different objection put forth by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Henri_Poincar%C3%A9" title=3D"Henri Poincar=C3=A9">Henri Poincar=C3=
=A9</a> is that defining sets using the axiom schemas of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_schema_of_specification" title=3D"Axiom schema=
 of specification">specification</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Axiom_schema_of_replacement" title=3D"Axiom schema of replacement">r=
eplacement</a>, as well as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axi=
om_of_power_set" title=3D"Axiom of power set">axiom of power set</a>, intro=
duces <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impredicativity" title=3D"Im=
predicativity">impredicativity</a>, a type of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Circular_definition" title=3D"Circular definition">circularity<=
/a>, into the definitions of mathematical objects. The scope of predicative=
ly founded mathematics, while less than that of the commonly accepted Zerme=
lo=E2=80=93Fraenkel theory, is much greater than that of constructive mathe=
matics, to the point that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomon_=
Feferman" title=3D"Solomon Feferman">Solomon Feferman</a> has said that "al=
l of scientifically applicable analysis can be developed [using predicative=
 methods]".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ludwig_Wittgenstein" title=
=3D"Ludwig Wittgenstein">Ludwig Wittgenstein</a> condemned set theory philo=
sophically for its connotations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Mathematical_platonism" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical platon=
ism">mathematical platonism</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-29"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> He wrote that "set theory is wrong", since it builds on the "nonsense" =
of fictitious symbolism, has "pernicious idioms", and that it is nonsensica=
l to talk about "all numbers".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-30"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Wittgenstein identified mathematics with algorithmic human deduction;<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERodych2018[httpsplatostanfordeduentrieswittgenstein=
-mathematicsWittInteConsForm_=C2=A72.1]_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTERodych2018[h=
ttpsplatostanfordeduentrieswittgenstein-mathematicsWittInteConsForm_%C2%A72=
.1]-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> the need for a secure foundation for mathematics seemed=
, to him, nonsensical.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERodych2018[httpsplatostan=
fordeduentrieswittgenstein-mathematicsWittLateCritSetTheoNonEnumVsNonDenu_=
=C2=A73.4]_32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Set_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTERodych2018[httpsplatostanfordeduentrieswitt=
genstein-mathematicsWittLateCritSetTheoNonEnumVsNonDenu_%C2%A73.4]-32"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Moreover, since human effort is necessarily finite, Wittgenstein's =
philosophy required an ontological commitment to radical <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructivism_(math)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Constructivism (math)">constructivism</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Finitism" title=3D"Finitism">finitism</a>. Meta-mathematica=
l statements =E2=80=93 which, for Wittgenstein, included any statement quan=
tifying over infinite domains, and thus almost all modern set theory =E2=80=
=93 are not mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERodych2018[httpsplatost=
anfordeduentrieswittgenstein-mathematicsWittInteFini_=C2=A72.2]_33-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_not=
e-FOOTNOTERodych2018[httpsplatostanfordeduentrieswittgenstein-mathematicsWi=
ttInteFini_%C2%A72.2]-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Few modern philosophers have adopted =
Wittgenstein's views after a spectacular blunder in <i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remarks_on_the_Foundations_of_Mathematics" title=3D"Re=
marks on the Foundations of Mathematics">Remarks on the Foundations of Math=
ematics</a></i>: Wittgenstein attempted to refute <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%B6del%27s_incompleteness_theorems" title=3D"G=C3=B6del=
's incompleteness theorems">G=C3=B6del's incompleteness theorems</a> after =
having only read the abstract. As reviewers <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Georg_Kreisel" title=3D"Georg Kreisel">Kreisel</a>, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Bernays" title=3D"Paul Bernays">Bernays</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Dummett" title=3D"Micha=
el Dummett">Dummett</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R._L.=
_Goodstein" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"R. L. Goodstein">Goodstein</a> a=
ll pointed out, many of his critiques did not apply to the paper in full. O=
nly recently have philosophers such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Crispin_Wright" title=3D"Crispin Wright">Crispin Wright</a> begun to r=
ehabilitate Wittgenstein's arguments.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERodych2018=
[httpsplatostanfordeduentrieswittgenstein-mathematicsWittGodeUndeMathProp_=
=C2=A73.6]_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Set_theory#cite_note-FOOTNOTERodych2018[httpsplatostanfordeduentrieswitt=
genstein-mathematicsWittGodeUndeMathProp_%C2%A73.6]-34"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category_theory" title=3D"C=
ategory theory">Category theorists</a> have proposed <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Topos_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Topos theor=
y">topos theory</a> as an alternative to traditional axiomatic set theory. =
Topos theory can interpret various alternatives to that theory, such as <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_constructivism" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical constructivism">constructivism</a>, fin=
ite set theory, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turing_Machine=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Turing Machine">computable</a> set theory.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_not=
e-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Topoi also give a natural setting for forcing and discuss=
ions of the independence of choice from ZF, as well as providing the framew=
ork for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pointless_topology" title=
=3D"Pointless topology">pointless topology</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Stone_space" title=3D"Stone space">Stone spaces</a>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Set_theory#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An active area of research is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Univalent_foundations" title=3D"Univalent foundations">univalent fou=
ndations</a> and related to it <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hom=
otopy_type_theory" title=3D"Homotopy type theory">homotopy type theory</a>.=
 Within homotopy type theory, a set may be regarded as a homotopy 0-type, w=
ith <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_properties" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Universal properties">universal properties</a> of se=
ts arising from the inductive and recursive properties of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Higher_inductive_type" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Higher inductive type">higher inductive types</a>. Principles such as t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom_of_choice" title=3D"Axiom=
 of choice">axiom of choice</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Law_of_the_excluded_middle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Law of the=
 excluded middle">law of the excluded middle</a> can be formulated in a man=
ner corresponding to the classical formulation in set theory or perhaps in =
a spectrum of distinct ways unique to type theory. Some of these principles=
 may be proven to be a consequence of other principles. The variety of form=
ulations of these axiomatic principles allows for a detailed analysis of th=
e formulations required in order to derive various mathematical results.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-3=
9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Mathematical_education">Mat=
hematical education</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DSet_theory&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Mathematical education"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As set theory gained popularity as a foundation for modern mathematics, =
there has been support for the idea of introducing the basics of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_set_theory" title=3D"Naive set theory"=
>naive set theory</a> early in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mat=
hematics_education" title=3D"Mathematics education">mathematics education</=
a>.
</p><p>In the US in the 1960s, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/New_Math" title=3D"New Math">New Math</a> experiment aimed to teach basic =
set theory, among other abstract concepts, to <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Primary_school" title=3D"Primary school">primary school</a> stu=
dents but was met with much criticism.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-40"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> The math syllabus in European schools followed this trend and cur=
rently includes the subject at different levels in all grades. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Venn_diagram" title=3D"Venn diagram">Venn diag=
rams</a> are widely employed to explain basic set-theoretic relationships t=
o primary school students (even though <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/John_Venn" title=3D"John Venn">John Venn</a> originally devised them a=
s part of a procedure to assess the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Validity_(logic)" title=3D"Validity (logic)">validity</a> of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inference" title=3D"Inference">inferences</a> =
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Term_logic" title=3D"Term logic=
">term logic</a>).
</p><p>Set theory is used to introduce students to <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Logical_operators" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Logical =
operators">logical operators</a> (NOT, AND, OR), and semantic or rule descr=
iption (technically <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intensional_de=
finition" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Intensional definition">intensiona=
l definition</a>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ruda2011_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-Ruda2011-41"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> of sets (e.g. "months starting with the letter <i>A</i>"), which m=
ay be useful when learning <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compute=
r_programming" title=3D"Computer programming">computer programming</a>, sin=
ce <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_logic" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Boolean logic">Boolean logic</a> is used in various <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language" title=3D"Programmin=
g language">programming languages</a>. Likewise, sets and other collection-=
like objects, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiset" ti=
tle=3D"Multiset">multisets</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/List_(abstract_data_type)" title=3D"List (abstract data type)">lists</a>, =
are common <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(abstract_data_type=
)" title=3D"Set (abstract data type)">datatypes</a> in computer science and=
 programming.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><br>
In addition to that, certain sets are commonly used in mathematical teachin=
g (such as the sets <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline=
